  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Lament of Parting
  author: Jeong Po
  language: eng
  text: |-
    At fifteen, I was foolish and vain,
    Mocking others' sorrow at farewell—
    How could I know that I, too, would taste such pain?
    In one night my dark hair turned white as hoarfrost.

    I loved you with all my heart, yet could not hold you fast.
    My breast swells with longing, with unmet promises of wind and cloud.
    Your glory awaits—men have their seasons of renown,
    But a woman's beauty—how few seasons does it have?

    I swallow my cries, dare not curse this bitter parting.
    Thinking again, I regret we did not meet too late.
    Already I have passed Kangseong on the journey home,
    Cradling my zither, long I stood by the river's southern shore.

    I envy the wild geese that fly the river—
    They follow each other through ten thousand miles of longing.
    I cannot even look upon my mirror,
    Much less dress myself in silk for the feast.

    When sorrow weighs upon me, I seek only sleep,
    Hoping to smile in dreams and return holding your hand.
    But heaven's distant paths—even my dreaming soul cannot find its way.
    How can a human heart ever find solace in this yearning?
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'Kangseong County (康城縣): A place name marking the journey away, emphasizing the irreversible nature of the separation.'
  - key: ''
    value: The contrast between men's pursuit of glory and a woman's fading beauty reflects the gendered constraints of classical society, deepening the speaker's sense of helplessness.
  - key: ''
    value: The wild geese (江上鴈) are a classical symbol of fidelity and couples traveling together, intensifying the speaker's isolation.
